  "noteInfoExplanationAdditionalTitle": "Additional context",
  "noteInfoStrategySheetTitle": "What is recognition mode?",
  "noteInfoStrategySheetDescription": "This field shows how the app produced the final text. The selected mode depends on the model and the shape of the recording.",
  "noteInfoStrategySheetNote": "Streaming: text appears as the audio is being processed, so progress is easier to follow. This mode is useful when responsiveness matters on longer recordings.\n\nSingle pass: the model processes the recording in one go without splitting it into parts. This is a simple path that works well for shorter and more even audio.\n\nChunked: the recording is split into several parts, and each part is transcribed separately. This helps the app handle longer audio more steadily without putting everything into one pass.\n\nChunked with VAD: before transcription, the system tries to separate speech from pauses and silence. This is especially useful when the recording contains long quiet gaps or a lot of silence.",
  "noteInfoSpeechDetectionSheetTitle": "What is speech detection?",
  "noteInfoSpeechDetectionSheetDescription": "This mode tries to separate actual speech from pauses and silence. When speech detection is enabled, the model processes only the parts where voice is present.",
  "noteInfoSpeechDetectionSheetNote": "This is usually helpful for long recordings with pauses: less unnecessary work, faster processing, and more stable segmentation.",
  "noteInfoFallbackModeSheetTitle": "What is fallback mode?",
  "noteInfoFallbackModeSheetDescription": "This is a safety path for the VAD pipeline. If speech-detection-based processing looks unreliable or does not fit the current audio well, the system can run transcription again with a simpler and more reliable path.\n\nThis fallback does not manually change the note. It only switches to another technical path to reduce the risk of an empty or truncated result.",
  "noteInfoFallbackModeSheetNote": "If this field says “Yes”, the first attempt used VAD, but the final text came from the fallback pass.",
  "noteInfoTextNormalizationSheetTitle": "What is text normalization?",
  "noteInfoTextNormalizationSheetDescription": "Text normalization converts recognized speech into a more natural written form. This usually affects numbers, dates, time, currencies, and other entities that the model may hear in one form and write in another.\n\nFor example, a spoken form can become easier to read without changing the meaning.",
  "noteInfoTextNormalizationSheetNote": "Not every model family reports whether this normalization was applied, so this field can sometimes show “No data”.",
  "noteInfoAutoPunctuationSheetTitle": "What is auto punctuation?",
  "noteInfoAutoPunctuationSheetDescription": "Auto punctuation adds periods, commas, and other punctuation marks to recognized text so it reads more like regular written language.\n\nThis is especially noticeable on long phrases: the text becomes easier to scan, copy, and edit.",
  "noteInfoAutoPunctuationSheetNote": "Some models insert punctuation themselves, while others do not report this information at all, so this field may show “No data”.",

